    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ab, Ad). Stands occur scattered along edges of salt marshes in natural and restored sites around the San Francisco Bay and in high tidal brackish marshes of San Pablo Bay and Suisun Marsh. <i>Centromadia pungens</i> ssp. <i>maritima</i> is dominant with <i>Baccharis douglasii, Euthamia occidentalis, Symphyotrichum chilense,</i> and <i>S. subulatum</i> (Baye et al. 2000). Stands with <i>C. parryi</i> ssp. <i>parryi</i> and ssp. <i>congdonii</i> were locally common in the South Bay salt marshes in the past (Munz 1959), as were stands of <i>C. pungens</i> ssp. <i>maritima,</i> but they are scarce today.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Au-z). Observations from the southern San Joaquin Valley include reports of summer flowering <i>C. pungens,</i> covering parts of the section (Webster 1981); they occur on alkaline flats.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-d). Stands include a relatively uncommon association of small (< 200 m2), shallow, claypan vernal pools in the southern subsections (Barbour et al. 2007b). The pools have <i>Medicago polymorpha, Phalaris lemmonii,</i> and <i>Trifolium</i> spp. on low-terrace landforms on the Riverbank geomorphic surface.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bk). Stands occupy edges of vernal flats in western Riverside Co.; they have an assortment of nonnative and native species, including <i>Croton setigerus</i> and <i>Lasthenia californica.</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
